WEBVTT


00:00:43.010 --> 00:00:54.170
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:55.179
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:00:55.179 --> 00:00:56.679
GWEN IFILL: And I'm Gwen Ifill.

00:00:56.679 --> 00:01:01.619
Welcome to this "PBS NewsHour" special coverage
of the first debate between the two major-party

00:01:01.619 --> 00:01:05.210
presidential candidates, Hillary Clinton and
Donald Trump.

00:01:05.210 --> 00:01:09.480
The stage is set at Hofstra University on
Long Island, New York.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:14.440
With the election 43 days away the race tightening,
a lot is on the line tonight, Judy.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:18.610
JUDY WOODRUFF: It certainly is, Gwen, and
given that this is the first time these two

00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:21.500
have faced each other one on one.

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:24.300
Lester Holt of NBC News will be moderating.

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:30.130
Joining us at the table are our regular contributors,
syndicated columnist Mark Shields, New York

00:01:30.130 --> 00:01:34.720
Times columnist David Brooks, and from The
Cook Political Report, Amy Walter.

00:01:34.720 --> 00:01:37.500
We welcome all you have here for the next
two hours.

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:38.970
Amy, let's start with you.

00:01:38.970 --> 00:01:39.970
What are you looking for?

00:01:39.970 --> 00:01:41.890
AMY WALTER, The Cook Political Report: Each
of these candidates has an enthusiasm gap

00:01:41.890 --> 00:01:42.990
problem within their own party.

00:01:42.990 --> 00:01:45.000
So, they have got to get their partisans fired
up.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:46.800
For Hillary Clinton, it's young people.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:50.870
For Donald Trump, he's got to get those white
college-educated voters back into the Republican

00:01:50.870 --> 00:01:51.960
fold, where they have been.

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:55.690
And then they have got to get those voters,
both of them, who are torn, don't like either

00:01:55.690 --> 00:01:58.050
choice they have in front of them, to pick
them.

00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:02.080
GWEN IFILL: Mark Shields, what would you -- surprise
you the most of what these candidates might

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:03.080
or might not do tonight?

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:05.229
MARK SHIELDS: Does Donald Trump dare to be
boring?

00:02:05.229 --> 00:02:09.990
Does he come out sedated/presidential?

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:15.180
And can Hillary Clinton, who is a marvelous
and superior deliverer of information, make

00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:17.690
an emotional connection with American voters?

00:02:17.690 --> 00:02:19.799
JUDY WOODRUFF: David, what are you on the
edge of your seat looking for?

00:02:19.799 --> 00:02:21.530
DAVID BROOKS: We have been around each other
too long.

00:02:21.530 --> 00:02:22.680
I wrote down emotional connection.

00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:23.680
(LAUGHTER)

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:24.680
MARK SHIELDS: Did you?

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:25.680
DAVID BROOKS: This is not a cognitive night.

00:02:25.680 --> 00:02:26.680
This is not philosophy.

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:28.150
This is not grand strategy.

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:33.069
It's moment of intimacy, that unscripted moment
when the unconscious is revealed that will

00:02:33.069 --> 00:02:36.370
be replayed on YouTube over and over and over
again.

00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:39.719
And so it's just, is he commanding or is he
cruel?

00:02:39.719 --> 00:02:43.889
Is she relatable and does she seem calmly
smart?

00:02:43.889 --> 00:02:47.630
And it's whether people get that vibe, the
first they vibe, that will determine the night.

00:02:47.630 --> 00:02:49.889
GWEN IFILL: Is this about what they know or
who they are?

00:02:49.889 --> 00:02:53.349
AMY WALTER: Well, I think it's mostly about
who they are.

00:02:53.349 --> 00:02:58.129
For voters at this stage of the game, they
are looking up on that dais to see who they

00:02:58.129 --> 00:03:02.810
can spend the next four years with, who they
want to invite into their homes moment after

00:03:02.810 --> 00:03:03.810
moment.

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:05.639
Many voters say, I don't want either one of
them in there.

00:03:05.639 --> 00:03:06.639
GWEN IFILL: A lot of them.

00:03:06.639 --> 00:03:07.900
AMY WALTER: A lot of voters are saying that.

00:03:07.900 --> 00:03:10.799
But this is the one maybe that they're not
going to like, but they will feel comfortable

00:03:10.799 --> 00:03:11.799
enough.

00:03:11.799 --> 00:03:15.540
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, Mark, people are going
to be fact-checking this debate.

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:19.469
They're going to be raising questions about
whether what either one of them said was correct

00:03:19.469 --> 00:03:20.469
or not.

00:03:20.469 --> 00:03:21.510
MARK SHIELDS: No, you're right, Judy.

00:03:21.510 --> 00:03:24.730
And if it's what they know, it will be a short
evening...

00:03:24.730 --> 00:03:25.730
(LAUGHTER)

00:03:25.730 --> 00:03:31.129
MARK SHIELDS: ... for the Republican nominee,
whose knowledge bank has been overdrawn.

00:03:31.129 --> 00:03:37.279
And I think it's about, more than anything
else, each case, what does he know, his command

00:03:37.279 --> 00:03:41.099
of it, is he comfortable with it, and who
she is.

00:03:41.099 --> 00:03:42.569
And I think that is really the question.

00:03:42.569 --> 00:03:44.480
DAVID BROOKS: And there is the gender politics.

00:03:44.480 --> 00:03:45.480
GWEN IFILL: OK.

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:47.200
Well, we're turning now to Lester Holt of
NBC News.

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:48.200
TRANSCRIPT START

00:03:48.200 --> 00:03:49.200
HOLT: Good evening from Hofstra University
in Hempstead, New York.

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:50.200
I'm Lester Holt, anchor of "NBC Nightly News."

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:51.200
I want to welcome you to the first presidential
debate.

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:52.200
The participants tonight are Donald Trump
and Hillary Clinton.

00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:53.200
This debate is sponsored by the Commission
on Presidential Debates, a nonpartisan, nonprofit

00:03:53.200 --> 00:03:54.200
organization.

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:58.349
The commission drafted tonight's format, and
the rules have been agreed to by the campaigns.

00:03:58.349 --> 00:04:03.889
The 90-minute debate is divided into six segments,
each 15 minutes long.

00:04:03.889 --> 00:04:10.389
We'll explore three topic areas tonight: Achieving
prosperity; America's direction; and securing

00:04:10.389 --> 00:04:11.959
America.

00:04:11.959 --> 00:04:16.139
At the start of each segment, I will ask the
same lead-off question to both candidates,

00:04:16.139 --> 00:04:19.310
and they will each have up to two minutes
to respond.

00:04:19.310 --> 00:04:23.370
From that point until the end of the segment,
we'll have an open discussion.

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:27.970
The questions are mine and have not been shared
with the commission or the campaigns.

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:32.160
The audience here in the room has agreed to
remain silent so that we can focus on what

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:33.870
the candidates are saying.

00:04:33.870 --> 00:04:39.190
I will invite you to applaud, however, at
this moment, as we welcome the candidates:

00:04:39.190 --> 00:04:43.140
Democratic nominee for president of the United
States, Hillary Clinton, and Republican nominee

00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:51.320
for president of the United States, Donald
J. Trump.

00:04:51.320 --> 00:04:52.940
(APPLAUSE)

00:04:52.940 --> 00:05:01.050
CLINTON: How are you, Donald?

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:02.670
(APPLAUSE)

00:05:02.670 --> 00:05:10.770
HOLT: Good luck to you.

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:12.390
(APPLAUSE)

00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:18.560
Well, I don't expect us to cover all the issues
of this campaign tonight, but I remind everyone,

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:21.580
there are two more presidential debates scheduled.

00:05:21.580 --> 00:05:25.880
We are going to focus on many of the issues
that voters tell us are most important, and

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:27.400
we're going to press for specifics.

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:32.160
I am honored to have this role, but this evening
belongs to the candidates and, just as important,

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:33.620
to the American people.

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:37.920
Candidates, we look forward to hearing you
articulate your policies and your positions,

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:40.850
as well as your visions and your values.

00:05:40.850 --> 00:05:42.980
So, let's begin.

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:46.440
We're calling this opening segment "Achieving
Prosperity."

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:49.190
And central to that is jobs.

00:05:49.190 --> 00:05:52.060
There are two economic realities in America
today.

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:56.950
There's been a record six straight years of
job growth, and new census numbers show incomes

00:05:56.950 --> 00:06:00.810
have increased at a record rate after years
of stagnation.

00:06:00.810 --> 00:06:06.320
However, income inequality remains significant,
and nearly half of Americans are living paycheck

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:07.860
to paycheck.

00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:12.070
Beginning with you, Secretary Clinton, why
are you a better choice than your opponent

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:16.780
to create the kinds of jobs that will put
more money into the pockets of American works?

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:22.120
CLINTON: Well, thank you, Lester, and thanks
to Hofstra for hosting us.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:27.930
The central question in this election is really
what kind of country we want to be and what

00:06:27.930 --> 00:06:30.680
kind of future we'll build together.

00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:35.060
Today is my granddaughter's second birthday,
so I think about this a lot.

00:06:35.060 --> 00:06:40.370
First, we have to build an economy that works
for everyone, not just those at the top.

00:06:40.370 --> 00:06:44.580
That means we need new jobs, good jobs, with
rising incomes.

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:46.530
I want us to invest in you.

00:06:46.530 --> 00:06:48.930
I want us to invest in your future.

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:54.630
That means jobs in infrastructure, in advanced
manufacturing, innovation and technology,

00:06:54.630 --> 00:06:59.530
clean, renewable energy, and small business,
because most of the new jobs will come from

00:06:59.530 --> 00:07:01.190
small business.

00:07:01.190 --> 00:07:04.110
We also have to make the economy fairer.

00:07:04.110 --> 00:07:10.840
That starts with raising the national minimum
wage and also guarantee, finally, equal pay

00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:12.060
for women's work.

00:07:12.060 --> 00:07:16.050
CLINTON: I also want to see more companies
do profit-sharing.

00:07:16.050 --> 00:07:20.370
If you help create the profits, you should
be able to share in them, not just the executives

00:07:20.370 --> 00:07:22.050
at the top.

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:28.900
And I want us to do more to support people
who are struggling to balance family and work.

00:07:28.900 --> 00:07:34.720
I've heard from so many of you about the difficult
choices you face and the stresses that you're

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:35.720
under.

00:07:35.720 --> 00:07:39.050
So let's have paid family leave, earned sick
days.

00:07:39.050 --> 00:07:42.620
Let's be sure we have affordable child care
and debt-free college.

00:07:42.620 --> 00:07:43.620
How are we going to do it?

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:47.760
We're going to do it by having the wealthy
pay their fair share and close the corporate

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:48.930
loopholes.

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:56.980
Finally, we tonight are on the stage together,
Donald Trump and I. Donald, it's good to be

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:58.670
with you.

00:07:58.670 --> 00:08:03.850
We're going to have a debate where we are
talking about the important issues facing

00:08:03.850 --> 00:08:05.150
our country.

00:08:05.150 --> 00:08:11.560
You have to judge us, who can shoulder the
immense, awesome responsibilities of the presidency,

00:08:11.560 --> 00:08:15.860
who can put into action the plans that will
make your life better.

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:20.140
I hope that I will be able to earn your vote
on November 8th.

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:21.940
HOLT: Secretary Clinton, thank you.

00:08:21.940 --> 00:08:23.440
Mr. Trump, the same question to you.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:26.700
It's about putting money -- more money into
the pockets of American workers.

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:27.700
You have up to two minutes.

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:29.150
TRUMP: 21:08:32 Thank you, Lester.

00:08:29.150 --> 00:08:32.459
Our jobs are fleeing the country.

00:08:32.459 --> 00:08:33.570
They're going to Mexico.

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:35.890
They're going to many other countries.

00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:40.029
You look at what China is doing to our country
in terms of making our product.

00:08:40.029 --> 00:08:44.930
They're devaluing their currency, and there's
nobody in our government to fight them.

00:08:44.930 --> 00:08:46.260
And we have a very good fight.

00:08:46.260 --> 00:08:48.070
And we have a winning fight.

00:08:48.070 --> 00:08:53.710
Because they're using our country as a piggy
bank to rebuild China, and many other countries

00:08:53.710 --> 00:08:55.480
are doing the same thing.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:58.760
So we're losing our good jobs, so many of
them.

00:08:58.760 --> 00:09:02.580
When you look at what's happening in Mexico,
a friend of mine who builds plants said it's

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:04.010
the eighth wonder of the world.

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:08.200
They're building some of the biggest plants
anywhere in the world, some of the most sophisticated,

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:09.860
some of the best plants.

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:13.610
With the United States, as he said, not so
much.

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:15.320
So Ford is leaving.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:18.990
You see that, their small car division leaving.

00:09:18.990 --> 00:09:21.860
Thousands of jobs leaving Michigan, leaving
Ohio.

00:09:21.860 --> 00:09:23.610
They're all leaving.

00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:25.710
And we can't allow it to happen anymore.

00:09:25.710 --> 00:09:29.750
As far as child care is concerned and so many
other things, I think Hillary and I agree

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:30.760
on that.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:36.160
We probably disagree a little bit as to numbers
and amounts and what we're going to do, but

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:38.730
perhaps we'll be talking about that later.

00:09:38.730 --> 00:09:43.110
But we have to stop our jobs from being stolen
from us.

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:50.360
We have to stop our companies from leaving
the United States and, with it, firing all

00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:51.360
of their people.

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:56.370
All you have to do is take a look at Carrier
air conditioning in Indianapolis.

00:09:56.370 --> 00:09:58.220
They left -- fired 1,400 people.

00:09:58.220 --> 00:09:59.950
They're going to Mexico.

00:09:59.950 --> 00:10:03.030
So many hundreds and hundreds of companies
are doing this.

00:10:03.030 --> 00:10:05.690
TRUMP: We cannot let it happen.

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:13.640
Under my plan, I'll be reducing taxes tremendously,
from 35 percent to 15 percent for companies,

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:15.339
small and big businesses.

00:10:15.339 --> 00:10:19.740
That's going to be a job creator like we haven't
seen since Ronald Reagan.

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:22.360
It's going to be a beautiful thing to watch.

00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:23.490
Companies will come.

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:24.490
They will build.

00:10:24.490 --> 00:10:25.490
They will expand.

00:10:25.490 --> 00:10:27.290
New companies will start.

00:10:27.290 --> 00:10:29.450
And I look very, very much forward to doing
it.

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:34.830
We have to renegotiate our trade deals, and
we have to stop these countries from stealing

00:10:34.830 --> 00:10:36.610
our companies and our jobs.

00:10:36.610 --> 00:10:38.880
HOLT: Secretary Clinton, would you like to
respond?

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:41.540
CLINTON: Well, I think that trade is an important
issue.

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:45.720
Of course, we are 5 percent of the world's
population; we have to trade with the other

00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:47.350
95 percent.

00:10:47.350 --> 00:10:50.690
And we need to have smart, fair trade deals.

00:10:50.690 --> 00:10:57.620
We also, though, need to have a tax system
that rewards work and not just financial transactions.

00:10:57.620 --> 00:11:02.880
And the kind of plan that Donald has put forth
would be trickle-down economics all over again.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:09.500
In fact, it would be the most extreme version,
the biggest tax cuts for the top percent of

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:11.870
the people in this country than we've ever
had.

00:11:11.870 --> 00:11:17.210
I call it trumped-up trickle-down, because
that's exactly what it would be.

00:11:17.210 --> 00:11:20.030
That is not how we grow the economy.

00:11:20.030 --> 00:11:24.740
We just have a different view about what's
best for growing the economy, how we make

00:11:24.740 --> 00:11:28.830
investments that will actually produce jobs
and rising incomes.

00:11:28.830 --> 00:11:31.700
I think we come at it from somewhat different
perspectives.

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:33.170
I understand that.

00:11:33.170 --> 00:11:39.680
You know, Donald was very fortunate in his
life, and that's all to his benefit.

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:45.339
He started his business with $14 million,
borrowed from his father, and he really believes

00:11:45.339 --> 00:11:50.240
that the more you help wealthy people, the
better off we'll be and that everything will

00:11:50.240 --> 00:11:51.240
work out from there.

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:52.930
I don't buy that.

00:11:52.930 --> 00:11:54.430
I have a different experience.

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:55.740
My father was a small-businessman.

00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:57.360
He worked really hard.

00:11:57.360 --> 00:12:02.850
He printed drapery fabrics on long tables,
where he pulled out those fabrics and he went

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:07.580
down with a silkscreen and dumped the paint
in and took the squeegee and kept going.

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:12.790
And so what I believe is the more we can do
for the middle class, the more we can invest

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:18.460
in you, your education, your skills, your
future, the better we will be off and the

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:19.600
better we'll grow.

00:12:19.600 --> 00:12:21.710
That's the kind of economy I want us to see
again.

00:12:21.710 --> 00:12:22.710
21:12:21

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:23.710
HOLT: Let me follow up with Mr. Trump, if
you can.

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:28.050
You've talked about creating 25 million jobs,
and you've promised to bring back millions

00:12:28.050 --> 00:12:29.790
of jobs for Americans.

00:12:29.790 --> 00:12:34.330
How are you going to bring back the industries
that have left this country for cheaper labor

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:35.330
overseas?

00:12:35.330 --> 00:12:38.920
How, specifically, are you going to tell American
manufacturers that you have to come back?

00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:44.050
TRUMP: Well, for one thing -- and before we
start on that -- my father gave me a very

00:12:44.050 --> 00:12:48.430
small loan in 1975, and I built it into a
company that's worth many, many billions of

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:52.279
dollars, with some of the greatest assets
in the world, and I say that only because

00:12:52.279 --> 00:12:54.520
that's the kind of thinking that our country
needs.

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:56.250
Our country's in deep trouble.

00:12:56.250 --> 00:13:00.580
We don't know what we're doing when it comes
to devaluations and all of these countries

00:13:00.580 --> 00:13:01.960
all over the world, especially China.

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:05.540
They're the best, the best ever at it.

00:13:05.540 --> 00:13:08.900
What they're doing to us is a very, very sad
thing.

00:13:08.900 --> 00:13:10.220
So we have to do that.

00:13:10.220 --> 00:13:12.260
We have to renegotiate our trade deals.

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:16.370
And, Lester, they're taking our jobs, they're
giving incentives, they're doing things that,

00:13:16.370 --> 00:13:17.370
frankly, we don't do.

00:13:17.370 --> 00:13:19.980
Let me give you the example of Mexico.

00:13:19.980 --> 00:13:20.980
They have a VAT tax.

00:13:20.980 --> 00:13:22.520
We're on a different system.

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:26.279
When we sell into Mexico, there's a tax.

00:13:26.279 --> 00:13:29.720
When they sell in -- automatic, 16 percent,
approximately.

00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:32.540
When they sell into us, there's no tax.

00:13:32.540 --> 00:13:34.690
It's a defective agreement.

00:13:34.690 --> 00:13:38.560
It's been defective for a long time, many
years, but the politicians haven't done anything

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:39.560
about it.

00:13:39.560 --> 00:13:44.010
Now, in all fairness to Secretary Clinton
-- yes, is that OK?

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:45.010
Good.

00:13:45.010 --> 00:13:46.770
I want you to be very happy.

00:13:46.770 --> 00:13:48.610
It's very important to me.

00:13:48.610 --> 00:13:53.399
But in all fairness to Secretary Clinton,
