debate, whether it was on question of the
birtherism, on his taxes, his support for

01:41:10.230 --> 01:41:16.389
the Iraq War, the debate about women, and
his things he said about women, about stamina.

01:41:16.389 --> 01:41:23.300
This was a debate in which she was able -- and
I think that Mark is completely right. Trump

01:41:23.300 --> 01:41:27.320
made it about himself, but she helped him
to make it about himself.

01:41:27.320 --> 01:41:34.059
Look, she didn't provide the vision. I think
that there are a lot of folks, even on the

01:41:34.059 --> 01:41:39.690
Democratic side, looking for that sense of,
what is the bigger message of Hillary Clinton?

01:41:39.690 --> 01:41:46.800
She's very smart. She has all of the facts
outlined. She has all the policy papers up

01:41:46.800 --> 01:41:47.800
on her Web site.

01:41:47.800 --> 01:41:54.419
But the bigger, sort of cohesive vision for
where we take America, I just -- I don't know

01:41:54.419 --> 01:41:56.889
that we still saw that in this debate.

01:41:56.889 --> 01:42:00.489
JUDY WOODRUFF: David, how do you see this?
Did either one of them do what they needed

01:42:00.489 --> 01:42:01.489
to do tonight?

01:42:01.489 --> 01:42:04.800
DAVID BROOKS: Well, it wasn't -- if what they
needed to do was make me feel better about

01:42:04.800 --> 01:42:08.610
the country, they failed. It was the opposite
of elevating on both sides.

01:42:08.610 --> 01:42:12.559
I thought, for the first half-hour, that Donald
Trump was winning. And I thought that was

01:42:12.559 --> 01:42:18.079
because, he may be obnoxious, but he is a
change agent. And the first half-hour was

01:42:18.079 --> 01:42:19.389
on his turf.

01:42:19.389 --> 01:42:22.860
And her answers, Hillary Clinton's answers,
went it was on -- gets to policy, it can't

01:42:22.860 --> 01:42:26.820
just be three things. It has to be 16 things.
And you get in laundry list mode.

01:42:26.820 --> 01:42:30.780
Then she started attacking him. And she had
two devastatingly good answers, on the birther

01:42:30.780 --> 01:42:34.820
issue and the tax return issue, which were
really good assaults on him. So, even though

01:42:34.820 --> 01:42:38.159
she's not good at describing a policy, she's
really good at going after him.

01:42:38.159 --> 01:42:43.219
And then the debate got on, and Donald Trump
became Donald Trump. And with every answer,

01:42:43.219 --> 01:42:47.709
it was digging it a little deeper. His birther
answer was abysmal, and bunch of bad answers

01:42:47.709 --> 01:42:53.019
all in a row. The race issue was terrible,
the looks issue, bad.

01:42:53.019 --> 01:42:56.789
And so he just -- at his lack of preparation,
and, frankly, a lot of his policies and his

01:42:56.789 --> 01:43:00.829
character just got worse and worse and worse.
So, I think you would have to say this was

01:43:00.829 --> 01:43:01.829
a Clinton night.

01:43:01.829 --> 01:43:06.709
GWEN IFILL: John Yang is in -- at Hofstra
University for us tonight. He's at the site

01:43:06.709 --> 01:43:08.059
of tonight's debate.

01:43:08.059 --> 01:43:11.379
And I'm wondering what the scene is like there,
John, how it's going over.

01:43:11.379 --> 01:43:16.840
JOHN YANG: Well, I tell you, the spinners
are just coming out. I'm just in front of

01:43:16.840 --> 01:43:19.539
the Donald Trump holding room.

01:43:19.539 --> 01:43:26.579
You can see them coming by here. Before, Senator
Claire McCaskill came by. She's obviously

01:43:26.579 --> 01:43:31.630
a supporter of Secretary Clinton. She was
telling me that she felt -- and this is sort

01:43:31.630 --> 01:43:36.840
of the line coming out of their -- the Clinton
room tonight -- that Donald Trump, once again,

01:43:36.840 --> 01:43:39.340
they say, showed that he wasn't prepared to
be president.

01:43:39.340 --> 01:43:44.959
They say that this was -- they say that it
came right from the top, when the secretary

01:43:44.959 --> 01:43:52.129
was able to give what they say -- what they're
saying was a coherent policy about providing

01:43:52.129 --> 01:43:54.519
jobs in America. But he wasn't.

01:43:54.519 --> 01:44:00.860
I tried to -- Governor Christie went by, wouldn't
stop. I'm trying to see if I can get someone

01:44:00.860 --> 01:44:04.510
from the Trump campaign to get their reaction.

01:44:04.510 --> 01:44:07.209
But, so far, that's what we have gotten so
far.

01:44:07.209 --> 01:44:10.590
GWEN IFILL: OK, John, we're going to let you
keep searching for people in the room to talk

01:44:10.590 --> 01:44:11.909
to. And we will get back to you.

01:44:11.909 --> 01:44:16.769
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Mark, I want to come to
you, because was there any -- David was saying

01:44:16.769 --> 01:44:20.189
that Donald Trump did better in the first
half-hour, when they talked about jobs, and

01:44:20.189 --> 01:44:25.010
he talked about jobs leaving the country.
Did Hillary Clinton ever have an answer to

01:44:25.010 --> 01:44:26.010
that?

01:44:26.010 --> 01:44:29.030
MARK SHIELDS: Well, I thought -- I mean, she
was defensive. There's no question about it.

01:44:29.030 --> 01:44:30.860
She was defensive on the TPP.

01:44:30.860 --> 01:44:35.340
But her answer that there were more manufacturing
jobs -- she did the defense of her husband's

01:44:35.340 --> 01:44:40.439
economic record, not a very -- a rather tepid
defense. There was a hell of a defense to

01:44:40.439 --> 01:44:45.289
be made for Bill Clinton's eight years of
22 million jobs and the lowest unemployment

01:44:45.289 --> 01:44:48.349
rates for African-Americans in the history
of the country, balancing the budget.

01:44:48.349 --> 01:44:52.519
She did -- she just said more manufacturing
jobs in the '90s.

01:44:52.519 --> 01:44:56.820
But I want to say, in defense of Trump, and
not to be totally -- I have never heard a

01:44:56.820 --> 01:45:00.729
presidential candidate -- and I have heard
40 of them -- say, I'm extremely underleveraged.

01:45:00.729 --> 01:45:01.729
(LAUGHTER)

01:45:01.729 --> 01:45:05.879
MARK SHIELDS: I mean, that was a rather remarkable
statement, if you think about it.

01:45:05.879 --> 01:45:11.289
And when he talked about not paying taxes,
he said, it would be squandered, too. That's

01:45:11.289 --> 01:45:18.429
why he didn't pay any taxes. And I thought
those were -- the explanation, the one that

01:45:18.429 --> 01:45:22.449
will be most memorable, was that, who hacked
the DNC? It wasn't Russia. Could have been

01:45:22.449 --> 01:45:25.369
Russia. Could have been China. Could have
been some other country, or it could have

01:45:25.369 --> 01:45:28.110
been someone sitting on the bed that weighs
400 pounds.

01:45:28.110 --> 01:45:30.479
I don't know if the bed weighs 400 pounds
or the person weighs 400 pounds.

01:45:30.479 --> 01:45:31.479
(LAUGHTER)

01:45:31.479 --> 01:45:33.940
GWEN IFILL: And that is your definition of
"in defense of Donald Trump"?

01:45:33.940 --> 01:45:35.550
MARK SHIELDS: That was it. That was it.

01:45:35.550 --> 01:45:36.550
GWEN IFILL: Just checking.

01:45:36.550 --> 01:45:37.550
DAVID BROOKS: He touched me. I'm underleveraged
myself.

01:45:37.550 --> 01:45:38.550
(CROSSTALK)

01:45:38.550 --> 01:45:39.550
(LAUGHTER)

01:45:39.550 --> 01:45:42.159
GWEN IFILL: Can we talk a little bit about
the line of questioning on race?

01:45:42.159 --> 01:45:47.449
Because when -- I never heard presidential
candidate in the debate call the person that

01:45:47.449 --> 01:45:52.169
he or she is running against, use the word
racist, three times. And also, when he was

01:45:52.169 --> 01:45:55.880
asked about race, Donald Trump talked about
law and order.

01:45:55.880 --> 01:45:59.250
What were the dog whistles in the room? Or
maybe they weren't even dog whistles. Everybody

01:45:59.250 --> 01:46:00.250
could hear them.

01:46:00.250 --> 01:46:01.250
AMY WALTER: Yes.

01:46:01.250 --> 01:46:06.860
Donald Trump's answer, whenever there's an
issue on -- whether it's on race, whether

01:46:06.860 --> 01:46:11.059
it's on policing, whether it's on terrorism,
he always comes back to, it's all about law

01:46:11.059 --> 01:46:13.899
and order. We're going to get the police.
We're going to get stuff done, because that's

01:46:13.899 --> 01:46:15.530
how things work.

01:46:15.530 --> 01:46:22.360
And we also know that that is an answer that
is not a comfortable answer for many people

01:46:22.360 --> 01:46:29.230
in the African-American community and in -- among
nonwhite voters, about who gets profiled when

01:46:29.230 --> 01:46:34.760
we have stop and frisk programs, when we have
law and order, what that actually means.

01:46:34.760 --> 01:46:40.869
These were questions that were not the kinds
of questions that Donald Trump answers particularly

01:46:40.869 --> 01:46:45.340
well. But that's not who he's playing to.
We talked about this a lot during the convention.

01:46:45.340 --> 01:46:49.719
Throughout this -- throughout the convention,
throughout this debate, Donald Trump talked

01:46:49.719 --> 01:46:53.879
to the same people he's been talking to this
entire campaign. There are a group of voters

01:46:53.879 --> 01:47:01.079
out there who are white, who are working class
who he's done very, very well with. And those

01:47:01.079 --> 01:47:04.939
are voters he expects to take him all the
way throughout this election.

01:47:04.939 --> 01:47:08.480
And he's not interested in reaching out and
getting beyond that base.

01:47:08.480 --> 01:47:11.729
JUDY WOODRUFF: You know, David, picking up
what Amy is saying, it seems to me that much

01:47:11.729 --> 01:47:15.710
of this debate was on territory where Donald
Trump is uncomfortable, I mean, the whole

01:47:15.710 --> 01:47:20.579
birther question. Lester Holt raised that.
He pushed Donald Trump on that. He pushed

01:47:20.579 --> 01:47:24.110
him on his tax returns, which we have been
talking about.

01:47:24.110 --> 01:47:27.349
These were areas where Donald Trump was back
against the ropes.

01:47:27.349 --> 01:47:28.349
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

01:47:28.349 --> 01:47:31.699
I do think Holt was tougher on Trump than
on Clinton. Maybe there's more to work with

01:47:31.699 --> 01:47:36.340
there. And he certainly exposed some vulnerabilities.
The defense that "I have a country club in

01:47:36.340 --> 01:47:40.769
Palm Beach which allows in minorities," that's
not -- that is not your good defense.

01:47:40.769 --> 01:47:41.769
But...

01:47:41.769 --> 01:47:45.690
GWEN IFILL: Trump is apparently already tweeting
that there weren't good questions about e-mails,

01:47:45.690 --> 01:47:46.690
about Benghazi...

01:47:46.690 --> 01:47:47.690
DAVID BROOKS: Right.

01:47:47.690 --> 01:47:48.690
JUDY WOODRUFF: And the Clinton Foundation.

01:47:48.690 --> 01:47:49.690
DAVID BROOKS: And somewhat fair, actually.

01:47:49.690 --> 01:47:52.520
But here is way think it's going to happen.
I think he really looked bad on some of the

01:47:52.520 --> 01:47:57.520
-- especially some of the racial stuff, on
the gender stuff, a lot of stuff.

01:47:57.520 --> 01:48:02.610
And so I think we can expect his polls to
drop as after the convention season. But,

01:48:02.610 --> 01:48:07.699
as Amy said, that's not his audience. And,
two, he is thematically so consistent. We

01:48:07.699 --> 01:48:10.969
are under assault, we're under assault, we're
under assault.

01:48:10.969 --> 01:48:16.320
And it wouldn't surprise me if he then -- his
numbers then began to go up, as they have

01:48:16.320 --> 01:48:19.039
in the last couple weeks, with all this stuff.
He's already said all this before.

01:48:19.039 --> 01:48:22.249
GWEN IFILL: I might also add that, if you
want to know, we have been keeping track of

01:48:22.249 --> 01:48:25.519
the things that were true, the things that
were false that were said tonight on our Web

01:48:25.519 --> 01:48:30.250
site, PBS.org/NewsHour. Just go there and
find what all of our experts, including our

01:48:30.250 --> 01:48:33.809
own -- well, Margaret Warner, our own Paul
Solman are telling -- answering these questions.

01:48:33.809 --> 01:48:34.809
JUDY WOODRUFF: Pulling it together.

01:48:34.809 --> 01:48:39.820
GWEN IFILL: But facts -- facts seemed to be
an important issue here than -- or lack thereof,

01:48:39.820 --> 01:48:43.899
tonight, Mark. And that was also Hillary Clinton's
turf.

01:48:43.899 --> 01:48:46.659
MARK SHIELDS: Yes. No, that's where she is.

01:48:46.659 --> 01:48:53.679
But she can't give a short answer. That is
a real problem. There is a little bit of,

01:48:53.679 --> 01:48:59.739
let me tell you how much I know. And I -- I
don't even know the capital of Sweden, but

01:48:59.739 --> 01:49:04.899
I can tell you what the principal products
of Sweden are and how long, you know, Stockholm

01:49:04.899 --> 01:49:12.379
-- and I think that is -- but I have -- again,
there are moments in the debate which I think

01:49:12.379 --> 01:49:13.379
we can't ignore.

01:49:13.379 --> 01:49:18.280
And that is, "You don't learn a lot from the
tax returns, that, I can tell you," explaining

01:49:18.280 --> 01:49:23.679
why he hasn't released his own taxes, and
said paying no federal taxes makes me smart.

01:49:23.679 --> 01:49:29.929
Now, I'm sorry. I mean, the cops and E-4s
in the Marine Corps and schoolteachers and

01:49:29.929 --> 01:49:36.479
registered nurses who pay taxes every year,
I don't know if not paying taxes for the two

01:49:36.479 --> 01:49:40.070
years that he has on the record is a recommendation.

01:49:40.070 --> 01:49:41.070
(CROSSTALK)

01:49:41.070 --> 01:49:45.070
DAVID BROOKS: I would agree with you, if the
Republican debates hadn't happened.

01:49:45.070 --> 01:49:48.039
And maybe it's just the Republican audiences
are different. But the rules are a little

01:49:48.039 --> 01:49:51.869
different this year. And a lot of things where
he says, I'm smart, I got away with this,

01:49:51.869 --> 01:49:56.940
I do think that has some resonance in a country
of high-end social distrust. And I do think

01:49:56.940 --> 01:49:59.189
some of the rules are a little different applying
to him.

01:49:59.189 --> 01:50:02.579
MARK SHIELDS: Do you think those respectable
people who have come to him in the last few

01:50:02.579 --> 01:50:06.679
weeks, I mean, the thoughtful, have been kind
of overlooking it? Do you think they were

01:50:06.679 --> 01:50:07.679
made comfortable tonight?

01:50:07.679 --> 01:50:08.679
(CROSSTALK)

01:50:08.679 --> 01:50:09.679
DAVID BROOKS: Total squirming. Total squirming.

01:50:09.679 --> 01:50:10.679
(CROSSTALK)

01:50:10.679 --> 01:50:11.969
AMY WALTER: Yes. And that's really the question:
Did he pass the judgment test?

01:50:11.969 --> 01:50:16.269
But to the point of -- which I don't know
that he was able to pass the judgment, temperament

01:50:16.269 --> 01:50:19.929
test. I don't think that that was -- he gets
high marks on that.

01:50:19.929 --> 01:50:23.880
But on the question about where the country
feels that we're going, we're pretty evenly

01:50:23.880 --> 01:50:27.169
divided between whether -- and this is the
Wall Street Journal poll -- is our country

01:50:27.169 --> 01:50:31.500
losing ground or is our country making progress?
Forty-eight percent say losing ground. Forty-five

01:50:31.500 --> 01:50:33.039
percent say making progress.

01:50:33.039 --> 01:50:40.449
Not surprisingly, among white Americans, plus-11
losing ground, among nonwhite Americans, plus-28

01:50:40.449 --> 01:50:41.449
making progress.

01:50:41.449 --> 01:50:45.269
And so when you see these candidates literally
talking past each other, as you pointed out,

01:50:45.269 --> 01:50:48.019
on race issues, on so many other issues about
where we're going...

01:50:48.019 --> 01:50:49.019
GWEN IFILL: Taxes.

01:50:49.019 --> 01:50:52.030
AMY WALTER: ... on taxes, it's literally we
have a country that is seeing the direction

01:50:52.030 --> 01:50:53.030
that we're going in completely differently.

01:50:53.030 --> 01:50:56.810
JUDY WOODRUFF: I think all three of you were
saying before the debate that Hillary Clinton

01:50:56.810 --> 01:51:03.810
tonight needed to be more likable. She needed
to -- Mark, what was your term? She needed

01:51:03.810 --> 01:51:04.810
to...

01:51:04.810 --> 01:51:06.890
MARK SHIELDS: At the end of it, say, not a
bad egg.

01:51:06.890 --> 01:51:07.890
JUDY WOODRUFF: Not a bad egg.

01:51:07.890 --> 01:51:08.890
(CROSSTALK)

01:51:08.890 --> 01:51:11.249
MARK SHIELDS: Like to have in the carpool.

01:51:11.249 --> 01:51:13.090
JUDY WOODRUFF: But she did she do that tonight?

01:51:13.090 --> 01:51:14.449
MARK SHIELDS: In the PTA meeting.

01:51:14.449 --> 01:51:16.849
JUDY WOODRUFF: Did that happen or not?

01:51:16.849 --> 01:51:21.399
MARK SHIELDS: No. I don't think -- I don't
think -- she wasn't unlikable, but she certainly

01:51:21.399 --> 01:51:22.399
-- there wasn't any...

01:51:22.399 --> 01:51:23.399
AMY WALTER: What?

01:51:23.399 --> 01:51:27.959
MARK SHIELDS: There wasn't any point in which
you got a peek into her -- who she is, what

01:51:27.959 --> 01:51:28.979
makes her tick.

01:51:28.979 --> 01:51:32.280
GWEN IFILL: I never hear anybody ask whether
Donald Trump is likable.

01:51:32.280 --> 01:51:33.809
MARK SHIELDS: Oh, sure we do.

01:51:33.809 --> 01:51:34.809
GWEN IFILL: Yes?

01:51:34.809 --> 01:51:35.809
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

01:51:35.809 --> 01:51:36.809
GWEN IFILL: Yes?

01:51:36.809 --> 01:51:37.809
MARK SHIELDS: And he's thoroughly unlikable.

01:51:37.809 --> 01:51:38.809
(CROSSTALK)

01:51:38.809 --> 01:51:39.809
DAVID BROOKS: It's not really an open question.

01:51:39.809 --> 01:51:40.809
GWEN IFILL: Oh, I see. Oh, I see.

01:51:40.809 --> 01:51:41.809
(CROSSTALK)

01:51:41.809 --> 01:51:46.719
MARK SHIELDS: Well, the Wall Street Journal/NBC
poll, to come back to what Amy was just talking

01:51:46.719 --> 01:51:51.939
about, he started 28/59 favorable/unfavorable,
and now he's at 29.

01:51:51.939 --> 01:51:56.829
JUDY WOODRUFF: We're going quickly back to
Hofstra university in New York.

01:51:56.829 --> 01:51:58.070
Our John Yang is there.

01:51:58.070 --> 01:52:01.340
John, you have maybe found a Trump person?

01:52:01.340 --> 01:52:02.969
GWEN IFILL: Hi, John.

01:52:02.969 --> 01:52:08.949
JOHN YANG: I have got -- we have been talking
to some of the Trump supporters here now.

01:52:08.949 --> 01:52:13.650
They think -- and the one point that they
have been repeating over and over again is

01:52:13.650 --> 01:52:18.109
the point, actually, that he repeated over
and over again in the debate, was hitting

01:52:18.109 --> 01:52:25.659
at Clinton as a career politician, that reinforcing
this idea that he's the -- that career politicians

01:52:25.659 --> 01:52:30.329
like Hillary Clinton are the reason for the
problems we're seeing now.

01:52:30.329 --> 01:52:35.050
That's been a signature line of his campaign
and, in many ways, one reason for a lot of

01:52:35.050 --> 01:52:39.379
the support of the campaign. And that's what
we're hearing over and over again from the

01:52:39.379 --> 01:52:40.829
Trump supporters here tonight.

01:52:40.829 --> 01:52:43.899
GWEN IFILL: In fact, John, that was one of
the big lines tonight, which is that she has

01:52:43.899 --> 01:52:47.959
experience, but it's bad experience, right?
And so they are picking up on that.

01:52:47.959 --> 01:52:49.760
JOHN YANG: Right.

01:52:49.760 --> 01:52:52.769
JUDY WOODRUFF: So -- and, John, thank you.

01:52:52.769 --> 01:52:53.769
(CROSSTALK)

01:52:53.769 --> 01:52:54.769
JUDY WOODRUFF: Go ahead.

01:52:54.769 --> 01:52:56.209
JOHN YANG: No, go ahead.

01:52:56.209 --> 01:53:01.250
JUDY WOODRUFF: I was just going to bring it
back here and say to David, is that effective?

01:53:01.250 --> 01:53:03.749
Is that something that sticks that he keeps
repeating?

01:53:03.749 --> 01:53:05.409
DAVID BROOKS: I think it does, actually.

01:53:05.409 --> 01:53:09.619
If you looked at her, just take him out of
the debate, she does look like a career politician.

01:53:09.619 --> 01:53:13.579
She does repeat a lot of things. She doesn't
quite make human convention -- connection.

01:53:13.579 --> 01:53:17.209
And in year that's very unusual, she's not
that unusual.

01:53:17.209 --> 01:53:22.690
But I thought she did fine, and with some
devastatingly good assaults. But, again, as

01:53:22.690 --> 01:53:25.820
Mark said, he was the subject. And he did
negative.

01:53:25.820 --> 01:53:28.789
AMY WALTER: Well, and that's been the theme
throughout this campaign, right?

01:53:28.789 --> 01:53:33.959
Wherever the spotlight goes, if it's placed
on you, the candidate, you are likely to drop

01:53:33.959 --> 01:53:37.019
in the polls. When the spotlight gets to the
other candidate -- because this race has just

01:53:37.019 --> 01:53:39.649
simply been a referendum on who the worst
candidate is, right?

01:53:39.649 --> 01:53:44.150
And so when it -- if it goes to the spotlight
now on Donald Trump and how much he was on

01:53:44.150 --> 01:53:48.090
defense, it's not going to be how well Clinton
did as much as how poorly he did. And if it

01:53:48.090 --> 01:53:53.260
goes over to Hillary Clinton, then she becomes
the focus. Her numbers suffer.

01:53:53.260 --> 01:53:58.619
And at the end of the day, the candidate who
wins is the candidate who doesn't get in that

01:53:58.619 --> 01:54:00.599
spotlight for the last couple of weeks.

01:54:00.599 --> 01:54:04.789
GWEN IFILL: Let me ask a question about just
one big policy issue that he seemed to land

01:54:04.789 --> 01:54:09.429
a few blows on. And that was on trade, when
he kind of basically made the point that she

01:54:09.429 --> 01:54:13.079
had changed her mind. And he drove that point
home.

01:54:13.079 --> 01:54:15.709
MARK SHIELDS: He did.

01:54:15.709 --> 01:54:16.709
(CROSSTALK)

01:54:16.709 --> 01:54:21.030
MARK SHIELDS: The question I had, as he was
doing that, was -- are his interruptions a

01:54:21.030 --> 01:54:23.190
sign of strength or obnoxiousness?

01:54:23.190 --> 01:54:28.369
But he -- there's no question, he dominated
the dialogue. She was very much playing defense

01:54:28.369 --> 01:54:30.280
in the first part there.

01:54:30.280 --> 01:54:34.709
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, as David said, in the
first half-hour, it seemed to be that he was

01:54:34.709 --> 01:54:36.820
getting the better of a couple of points.

01:54:36.820 --> 01:54:41.859
But then, as we moved into the debate, it
seemed to me Hillary Clinton felt more comfortable

01:54:41.859 --> 01:54:44.540
coming after him and sticking with some...

01:54:44.540 --> 01:54:45.540
(CROSSTALK)

01:54:45.540 --> 01:54:47.530
MARK SHIELDS: Yes, she baited him. There's
no question.

01:54:47.530 --> 01:54:48.820
AMY WALTER: Oh, yes.

01:54:48.820 --> 01:54:53.909
The Donald was baited. And he not, in that
sense, go after her the way I thought he would.

01:54:53.909 --> 01:54:57.889
I thought his own defense of his positions
was really faulty.

01:54:57.889 --> 01:55:00.789
GWEN IFILL: Well, time for all three of you
to ask -- really quick answers.

01:55:00.789 --> 01:55:01.789
AMY WALTER: Uh-oh.

01:55:01.789 --> 01:55:04.409
GWEN IFILL: Expectations in advance, did they
meet your expectations afterward?

01:55:04.409 --> 01:55:06.760
AMY WALTER: Yes, they did.

01:55:06.760 --> 01:55:08.170
GWEN IFILL: OK.

01:55:08.170 --> 01:55:09.170
Mark?

01:55:09.170 --> 01:55:10.170
MARK SHIELDS: No.

01:55:10.170 --> 01:55:11.170
(LAUGHTER)

01:55:11.170 --> 01:55:13.609
MARK SHIELDS: My expectations have never been
met. No.

01:55:13.609 --> 01:55:15.609
JUDY WOODRUFF: We may ask you this question
again tomorrow.

01:55:15.609 --> 01:55:16.609
David?

01:55:16.609 --> 01:55:20.119
DAVID BROOKS: Not a kamikaze night for him.
So, it's not a career-ender, not a campaign-ender,

01:55:20.119 --> 01:55:21.510
but not a good night.

01:55:21.510 --> 01:55:24.219
GWEN IFILL: All right. I think I gave you,
like, one word.

01:55:24.219 --> 01:55:25.219
AMY WALTER: Yes.

01:55:25.219 --> 01:55:28.829
But I can say -- yes, agree that it was a
better night for Hillary Clinton, but it does

01:55:28.829 --> 01:55:32.349
not feel like it was the defining end-all,
be-all of this campaign.

01:55:32.349 --> 01:55:34.479
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, hey, we have only got
six weeks to go.

01:55:34.479 --> 01:55:37.280
GWEN IFILL: You know what that means. We are
going to have to come back and do it again

01:55:37.280 --> 01:55:42.079
right here at this table, maybe October 4
for the vice presidential debate.

01:55:42.079 --> 01:55:47.010
That concludes our coverage of the first presidential
debate, but there's whole lot more, as we

01:55:47.010 --> 01:55:52.010
were saying, online. You can watch highlights.
Plus, see how "NewsHour" staff, from Margaret

01:55:52.010 --> 01:55:57.309
Warner to Paul Solman, as you were saying,
and more put what the candidates said in context.

01:55:57.309 --> 01:55:58.309
That's all at PBS.org/NewsHour.

01:55:58.309 --> 01:55:59.769
I'm Gwen Ifill.

01:55:59.769 --> 01:56:01.920
JUDY WOODRUFF: And I'm Judy Woodruff.

01:56:01.920 --> 01:56:04.590
And join us right here for the "NewsHour"
tomorrow night.

01:56:04.590 --> 01:56:40.939
For all of us at the "PBS NewsHour," thank
you, and good night.

